U.K. Chancellor of the Exchequer NigelLawson said the recent dispute between the United States andWest Germany over economic policy was responsible for muchfinancial turmoil and that it should never have happened.    He said in a television interview the dispute had fannedfears of a breakdown in the cooperation which is so importantbetween finance ministers of the major nations.    He said the dispute was a row which should not havehappened and agreed that much of the blame lay with U.S.Treasury Secretary James Baker who had publicly criticised WestGermany for having raised its key interest rates. REUTER&#3;